# Typesetting Rules

Every paragraph, description, and body-text string must follow these rules.

## No short words at line endings

Never allow a word of 3 letters or fewer to sit at the end of a line. This includes:

- **1-letter:** a, I
- **2-letter:** of, at, in, on, to, or, by, an, as, is, it, if, so, up, we, no, do, be
- **3-letter:** the, and, for, but, nor, yet, are, was, has, its, can, our, his, her, who, how, not, you, all, new, now, one, out, use, may, did, get, let, say, she, too

Bind these to the **following** word with a non-breaking space so they can never dangle.

## Widow prevention

The last line of every paragraph must contain at least two words. Bind the final two words with a non-breaking space.

## Non-breaking space syntax

| Context | Syntax | Example |
|---------|--------|---------|
| Inside JS string `{"..."}` | `\u00A0` | `{"drove a\u00A0number."}` |
| Plain JSX text | `&nbsp;` or `&#160;` | `without a&nbsp;full-time&nbsp;hire.` |
| Data objects (`.ts` arrays) | `\u00A0` | `desc: "Built to\u00A0last."` |

## Number binding

Always bind a number to its unit or following noun: `13\u00A0years`, `60\u00A0days`, `12%\u00A0increase`, `a\u00A057%`.

## Text measure

Use `max-w-[60ch]` on paragraph containers. This produces ~55-75 actual characters per line, the target range.

## CSS safety net (already in globals.css)

`text-wrap: pretty` on `p, li, blockquote` and `text-wrap: balance` on headings are applied globally. These help but do **not** replace manual `\u00A0` placement.

## Examples

```tsx
// BAD — "a" can dangle, widow on "number."
{"Every campaign had to move a number."}

// GOOD
{"Every campaign had to move a\u00A0number."}
```

```tsx
// BAD — "or" can dangle at line end
companies entering new markets, or agencies

// GOOD
companies entering new markets, or&#160;agencies
```
